article.headline: Peja, Miller sew it up for Sacramento
article.linkText: Kings escape Seattle, finish 4-2 road trip
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Two comforting sights for Sacramento fans: Peja Stojakovic at the foul line and Brad Miller on the offensive glass. Stojakovic scored 29 points, hitting two key free throws with 11.7 seconds to play, and Miller added 28 points and 17 rebounds -- eight on the offensive end -- as the Kings beat the Seattle SuperSonics 110-103 on Saturday night. "We've struggled offensively the last three games, but we won them all," said Stojakovic, who shot 4-of-13 on 3-pointers. "That means our defense did it for us. We've just got to play hard on the defensive end and our shots are going to fall." Stojakovic, the NBA's top free throw shooter at 92 percent, made both of his late free throws for a 106-103 lead. The Sonics inbounded to Ray Allen, who missed a 3-point try from the left corner. "It was going in and came right out," Allen said. The ball rebounded to Miller, who added another pair of free throws with 7.8 seconds on the clock to seal the win, which wrapped up a 4-2 road trip over the past 10 days for the Kings. "We're happy to be 4-2," Mike Bibby said. "Now I'm going to go see my kids." Antonio Daniels started for the injured Brent Barry and scored a career-high 30 points for Seattle, which erased a 17-point deficit in the third quarter but lost its third straight. Daniels also had 11 assists. "You cannot relax on Seattle," Stojakovic said. "They have so many good shooters. We knew Ray Allen and Rashard Lewis were going to come out shooting, and that's what they did. Antonio, he was awesome." Allen had 20 points, Lewis added 17 and Vitaly Potapenko 12. It was the second time this week the Sonics came up short in an exciting finish. They lost 118-116 to visiting Dallas on Tuesday when Antoine Walker hit a jumper at the buzzer. "We can't hang our heads," Allen said. "We're giving these teams our best. Just a couple of plays here and there, and we have to play a little harder." Seattle led for the first time since the opening minutes when Allen hit a 12-footer with 6:21 left, putting the Sonics up 90-89. Stojakovic, 6-of-16 at that point, answered with a 3-pointer, but Allen matched it at the other end. The Kings led 104-103 with just under a minute to play when Stojakovic missed a wide-open 3-pointer. At the other end, Allen missed another 3-pointer but Daniels came away with the rebound. Potapenko drove but missed a runner in the lane, setting up a key possession for the Kings. Sacramento put the ball in Stojakovic's hands, and he drew a sixth foul on Lewis, then hit the two big free throws. "We had a shot from point blank that rolled out and the other team made some big shots," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. Miller had 16 points and eight rebounds in the first half, helping Sacramento offset a 5-of-11 shooting performance by Stojakovic in the opening 24 minutes. "He's not going to have an unbelievable night every night," Miller said. "But even when he's missing, he helps us offensively because he pulls the defense away from the basket." The Kings, the highest-scoring team in the league at 104.5 points a game, built a 54-41 lead at the break. The Sonics committed 10 turnovers in the first quarter, but only one in the second half. "We can't give those extra opportunities," McMillan said. The Sonics struggled to start the second half and Sacramento went up 65-48 after a three-point play by Vlade Divac. Seattle finally woke up, with Daniels and Lewis leading a rally that trimmed the deficit to 80-75 going into the fourth quarter. The Sonics also got inspired defense from Reggie Evans to close the third quarter with a 13-7 burst. Holding big leads has been a problem for Sacramento this season. "It's the one area we've got to work on, especially on the road," Miller said. "We get up and everything's hunky-dory. We're fortunate to get the win."

Game notes
McMillan was whistled for a technical early in the fourth quarter after protesting a foul against Evans. ... The Sonics and Kings meet again Tuesday in Sacramento. ... The Kings improved to 8-8 against Western Conference teams. ... Allen shot 5-for-21.
